  "description": "Issue #543: a `(print …)` statement's snapshot rule applies to the whole statement's evaluation, not each argument's own evaluation instant — a later argument's evaluation (calling `mutate`, which does `add 2 to :l`) mutates a live value an earlier argument (`:l`) also reads, so the `print` event's payload must show `:l` as `[1 2]` (post-mutation), not `[1]` (its value when only that argument had been evaluated). Both operands are snapshotted together, sharing one memo, only after every argument in the statement has finished evaluating.",
